            "answer_text": "It was different at different points in time, of course. But here\u2019s the stats (the figures include all allied contingents, like Italians, Romanians etc, not only Germans): At the time of the beginning of invasion of the USSR (June 1941) total nubers of Wehrmacht were: 3 800 000 in the ground forces, 1 680 000 in Luftwaffe, 404 000 in Kriegsmarine, 150 000 in Waffen-SS and 1 200 000 in the army of reserve (7 234 000 total). Out of these in the invasion of Soviet Union the following forces were involved: out of Ground forces 3 300 000 (86%), 150 000 of Waffen-SS (100%), and 250 000 of Luftwaffe (14%). By July 1943 total numbers of Wehrmaht were 6 815 000 personnel. Out of them 3 900 000 on the Eastern Front (57%), 180 000 in Finland (2,6%), 315 000 in Norway (4,6%), 110 000 in Denmark (1,6%), 1 370 000 in Western Europe (20%), 330 000 in Italy (4,8%) and 610 000 in the Balkans (9%). By April 1944 total numbers of Wehrmacht personnel were 7 849 000. Out of them 3 878 000 (49%) on the Eastern front, 31 000 in Norway and Denmark (0,03%), 1 873 000 in Western europe (23%), 961 000 (12%) in Italy and 826 000 on the Balkans also fighting the Soviets by that time (10,5%). ",
